   "source": [
    "# 3.\tHow do you decide when to go for deep learning for a project?"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "0ea22230",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# ML is the parent of DL\n",
    "\n",
    "You go for deep learning when the problem has complex patterns that simpler ML models struggle to capture, and when you have enough data, compute, and a real business reason to justify it.\n",
    "\n",
    "How to decide when to use deep learning\n",
    "1) Start with the nature of the problem\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning is a strong choice when the input is unstructured or highly complex, such as:\n",
    "\n",
    "images\n",
    "\n",
    "audio\n",
    "\n",
    "video\n",
    "\n",
    "natural language\n",
    "\n",
    "documents with layout + text\n",
    "\n",
    "high-dimensional sensor data\n",
    "\n",
    "These problems usually contain patterns that are hard to capture with manual feature engineering.\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples\n",
    "\n",
    "image classification\n",
    "\n",
    "object detection\n",
    "\n",
    "speech recognition\n",
    "\n",
    "chatbot / question answering\n",
    "\n",
    "OCR with complex document layouts\n",
    "\n",
    "fraud/anomaly detection with sequential behavior patterns\n",
    "\n",
    "For simple tabular business data, deep learning is often not the first choice.\n",
    "\n",
    "2) Check the type and amount of data\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning generally performs best when you have:\n",
    "\n",
    "large amounts of data\n",
    "\n",
    "enough labeled examples\n",
    "\n",
    "consistent data quality\n",
    "\n",
    "Why?\n",
    "Because neural networks learn features automatically, but they need many examples to do it well.\n",
    "\n",
    "Rule of thumb\n",
    "\n",
    "Small structured dataset → try traditional ML first\n",
    "\n",
    "Large unstructured dataset → deep learning becomes attractive\n",
    "\n",
    "Example:\n",
    "\n",
    "5,000 rows of customer churn data → XGBoost / Random Forest may beat deep learning\n",
    "\n",
    "5 million product images → deep learning is usually the better fit\n",
    "\n",
    "3) See whether feature engineering is too hard\n",
    "\n",
    "If building manual features is difficult, expensive, or unreliable, deep learning can help.\n",
    "\n",
    "Traditional ML often needs:\n",
    "\n",
    "handcrafted features\n",
    "\n",
    "domain-specific preprocessing\n",
    "\n",
    "heavy feature engineering effort\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning can automatically learn useful representations.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "For image classification:\n",
    "\n",
    "Traditional ML: edges, texture, corners, handcrafted descriptors\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning: CNN learns these features by itself\n",
    "\n",
    "So if the problem is such that useful features are hard to define manually, deep learning is a good option.\n",
    "\n",
    "4) Consider expected accuracy and business impact\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning is worth using when better performance has a clear payoff.\n",
    "\n",
    "Ask:\n",
    "\n",
    "Do we need state-of-the-art accuracy?\n",
    "\n",
    "Will a small gain in precision/recall improve revenue, safety, or user experience?\n",
    "\n",
    "Is this a core product capability?\n",
    "\n",
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "Medical image diagnosis: even a few % improvement may matter a lot\n",
    "\n",
    "Search relevance, recommendations, OCR quality, voice assistant quality: deep learning can be worth the complexity\n",
    "\n",
    "But if a simpler model already meets business goals, deep learning may be overkill.\n",
    "\n",
    "5) Evaluate compute, time, and infrastructure\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning needs more:\n",
    "\n",
    "training time\n",
    "\n",
    "GPU/accelerator resources\n",
    "\n",
    "memory\n",
    "\n",
    "deployment planning\n",
    "\n",
    "monitoring\n",
    "\n",
    "So before choosing it, ask:\n",
    "\n",
    "Do we have GPU access?\n",
    "\n",
    "Can the latency requirements support this model?\n",
    "\n",
    "Can the team maintain the model in production?\n",
    "\n",
    "Is inference cost acceptable?\n",
    "\n",
    "If the answer is no, a simpler ML approach may be better.\n",
    "\n",
    "6) Consider interpretability requirements\n",
    "\n",
    "If the project needs strong explainability, deep learning may not be ideal as the first option.\n",
    "\n",
    "Traditional models like:\n",
    "\n",
    "Linear Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "Logistic Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "Decision Trees\n",
    "\n",
    "Gradient Boosting with SHAP\n",
    "\n",
    "are usually easier to explain than deep neural networks.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example\n",
    "\n",
    "In credit scoring or regulated healthcare decisions, interpretability can be very important.\n",
    "\n",
    "So if explainability is a strict requirement, you may choose traditional ML unless deep learning gives a major advantage.\n",
    "\n",
    "7) Compare with simpler baselines first\n",
    "\n",
    "A good practical approach is:\n",
    "\n",
    "Understand the problem\n",
    "\n",
    "Build a simple baseline\n",
    "\n",
    "Measure performance\n",
    "\n",
    "Use deep learning only if needed\n",
    "\n",
    "This is important because many real-world tabular problems are solved very well by:\n",
    "\n",
    "Logistic Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "Random Forest\n",
    "\n",
    "XGBoost\n",
    "\n",
    "LightGBM\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning should usually be chosen because it clearly adds value, not just because it is popular.\n",
    "\n",
    "8) Use deep learning when transfer learning can help\n",
    "\n",
    "Even if your dataset is not huge, deep learning may still be a good option if pretrained models exist.\n",
    "\n",
    "Examples:\n",
    "\n",
    "BERT for NLP\n",
    "\n",
    "ResNet / EfficientNet / ViT for images\n",
    "\n",
    "Whisper-like speech models\n",
    "\n",
    "Layout-aware document models for OCR/document AI\n",
    "\n",
    "In such cases, you do not always need massive data from scratch. Fine-tuning a pretrained model can work very well.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is one of the biggest reasons deep learning is used more today.\n",
    "\n",
    "Very simple beginner language\n",
    "\n",
    "Use deep learning when:\n",
    "\n",
    "the problem is hard and has complex data\n",
    "\n",
    "data is large, especially images, text, audio, or video\n",
    "\n",
    "normal ML is not giving good results\n",
    "\n",
    "manual feature engineering is difficult\n",
    "\n",
    "you have enough compute and time\n",
    "\n",
    "Do not choose deep learning first for every project.\n",
    "For small, simple, structured data, traditional ML is often better.\n",
    "\n",
    "Interview answer in 5 lines\n",
    "\n",
    "I choose deep learning when the problem involves complex or unstructured data like images, text, audio, or video, where manual feature engineering is difficult. I also check whether sufficient data, compute resources, and business value are available. If interpretability and low latency are critical, I may prefer simpler models first. In practice, I usually build a traditional ML baseline and move to deep learning only if it provides a meaningful improvement. Transfer learning also makes deep learning practical even when labeled data is limited.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example-based explanation\n",
    "Example 1: Customer churn prediction\n",
    "\n",
    "Data:\n",
    "\n",
    "age\n",
    "\n",
    "salary\n",
    "\n",
    "tenure\n",
    "\n",
    "usage count\n",
    "\n",
    "region\n",
    "\n",
    "This is structured tabular data.\n",
    "\n",
    "Best first choice:\n",
    "\n",
    "Logistic Regression\n",
    "\n",
    "Random Forest\n",
    "\n",
    "XGBoost\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning is usually not the first choice here.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example 2: Detecting pneumonia from chest X-rays\n",
    "\n",
    "Data:\n",
    "\n",
    "image data\n",
    "\n",
    "complex patterns\n",
    "\n",
    "difficult manual features\n",
    "\n",
    "Best choice:\n",
    "\n",
    "CNN / vision model\n",
    "\n",
    "Here deep learning is very suitable.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example 3: Resume parsing / document understanding\n",
    "\n",
    "If the task involves:\n",
    "\n",
    "scanned documents\n",
    "\n",
    "layout\n",
    "\n",
    "text blocks\n",
    "\n",
    "tables\n",
    "\n",
    "variable formats\n",
    "\n",
    "Deep learning can work very well, especially with OCR + layout-aware transformers.\n",
    "\n",
    "Example 4: Sentiment analysis on customer reviews\n",
    "\n",
    "Text data is unstructured.\n",
    "\n",
    "Traditional ML can work with TF-IDF + Logistic Regression, but deep learning or transformers may be better when:\n",
    "\n",
    "language is nuanced\n",
    "\n",
    "dataset is large\n",
    "\n",
    "context matters a lot\n",
    "\n",
    "Practical decision checklist\n",
    "\n",
    "Ask these questions:\n",
    "\n",
    "Go for deep learning if:\n",
    "\n",
    "data is unstructured\n",
    "\n",
    "problem is complex\n",
    "\n",
    "enough data is available\n",
    "\n",
    "pretrained models exist\n",
    "\n",
    "accuracy gain matters\n",
    "\n",
    "compute and deployment support are available\n",
    "\n",
    "Prefer traditional ML if:\n",
    "\n",
    "data is tabular and limited\n",
    "\n",
    "interpretability is critical\n",
    "\n",
    "fast training/inference is needed\n",
    "\n",
    "baseline models already perform well\n",
    "\n",
    "team/infrastructure for DL is limited\n",
    "\n",
    "Real-world project way to answer\n",
    "\n",
    "In an interview, a strong practical answer is:\n",
    "\n",
    "I do not directly choose deep learning. First, I study the problem type, data volume, and business constraints. If the data is unstructured or the relationships are highly complex, deep learning becomes a strong option. Then I check whether I have enough data, compute, and production support. I also compare against simpler baseline models, because if traditional ML solves the problem with lower cost and better interpretability, I would prefer that. I use deep learning when its performance advantage justifies the added complexity.\n",
    "\n",
    "One-line memory trick\n",
    "\n",
    "Simple data → traditional ML first\n",
    "Complex unstructured data + enough scale → deep learning"
   ]
  },
